PayLoad.HelpText: The dimension modeling demand/customer orders
The level attribute of demand (each customer order has one or more line items)
The dimension representing time
The level (time buckets) at which availability and allocation of resources are determined
Dimension for modeling resources
The level attribute at which actual resource members exist
Attribute representing resource pools such as (contractors, to-be hires etc)
Property of resource group which indicates if the solver needs to create members (such as hires)

Characteristic dimension to hold characteristics, which model things like desired skills, desired locations etc. A resouce is associated with one or more characteristics (an employee has Java, C++ skills, and is located in Bangalore). Similarly an order is associated with one or more characteristics (a project from customer needs 2 resources with Java skills , onsite at location Dallas)
The level attribute in the characteristic dimension that holds the characteristic members
Dimension for modeling activities
The level attribute at which actual activity members (C++ training, obtaining visa etc. exist)
Activity Group (skill activities in a skill group vs visa procurement activities in another group)
Measure that represents the time spent in an activity (obtaining a visa or getting trained for a new skill)

Method used for computing the summary stats.  Valid options: default, slidingwindow, incremental.
(1) default - uses the full input to generate a single value (2) slidingwindow - uses a sliding window of specified size and computes summary for each window
(3) incremental: computes a running summary incrementally from first bucket to last.

Documentation: Powershell plugin that increments data by 20
Code:
Param([string] $inputFilePath)
$csvFile = (Import-Csv $inputFilePath | Select @{Name="Product.[Brand Name]"; Expression={$_.'Product.[Brand Name]'}},@{Name="Customer.[Customer Name]";Expression={$_.'Customer.[Customer Name]'}},@{Name="Date.[Reporting Month]";Expression={$_.'Date.[Reporting Month]'}},@{Name="Version.[Version Name]";Expression={$_.'Version.[Version Name]'}},@{Name = "ACPA Bill Back"; Expression = {[int32] $_.'ACPA Bill Back' + 20}})
$csvFile |  Export-Csv -path $inputFilePath -NoTypeInformation
